			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Zemi's guide to swarm kiting<a name="74109"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 7 05 11:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>This is a post I made on my guild's message board. We have a section for each class. I'm posting it here because there are many much more experienced bards than I, and I'm hoping to get some feedback on this guide, to see if there's anything I should change/keep the same/tweak. Thanks in advance!
<br />

<br />
*******************************************
<br />
Welcome to Swarm Kiting 101! Please note that swarming is going to be impossible until you have at least your 1st charm song, because it's all about the pets you make. 
<br />

<br />
First, a general definition to what swarm kiting really is. Swarming is a form of kiting that only the Bard class is able to do, mostly for our ability to cast and run at the same time. Druids quad, Mages use their pets, Bards swarm. The basics are, get a bunch of mobs to chase you, charm the nearest one, sic it on the next nearest one, and if all goes well all the mobs will aggro onto your pet. Just before your pet dies, break charm and use your chants to kill it so you get the experience.
<br />

<br />
Rules for swarming:
<br />
1. Never hit, smack, dot, snare, or otherwise do anything to the mobs to get them to chase you. Only swarm mobs that will aggro you just by running by them. The reason: Every time you damage or cast any spell on a mob, it adds a hate counter against you. You don't want the mobs mad at you otherwise they will chase you instead of aggroing onto your pet.
<br />

<br />
2. The best mobs to swarm kite are social mobs, meaning they will come to help out their buddies if you're attacking one. The reason: If they're social, they'll aggro what their friends are already fighting, which should be your pet.
<br />

<br />
3. NEVER hit or cast any spell on a mob in your swarm that is not your pet. It goes back to that hate counter thing. You don't want them to keep chasing you after you've charmed a pet, you want them all to stick to your pet.
<br />

<br />
4. If you are swarming and you have someone grouped with you (e.i. to &quot;power level&quot; them) it is VERY important that they understand they are to do NOTHING that will draw any of your mobs' attention. That means no hitting of mobs, no shooting bows, no casting any spells on them OR you OR themselves. They should basically sit on their hands and DO NOTHING. In swarm kiting, if they attract the attention of one mob, they attract the attention of ALL the mobs, and they do NOT want that kind of aggro! lol That kind of aggro will get you killed in about 3 seconds (this is not a joke!)
<br />

<br />
The Basics:
<br />
Song Lineup:
<br />
Depending on what level you are will determine which songs you should have available to you. The basic mid-level (45+) line-up should include:
<br />
Charm song
<br />
Invis song
<br />
Selos
<br />
Snare song (for when the last mob is low in health and starts running)
<br />
A couple dots
<br />
Heal song and/or mana song (yes, your charm song uses mana, and bard mana regen is horrible so it's good to have mana song during downtime)
<br />

<br />
Starting your swarm
<br />
Once you pick your camp and have all your songs up you're ready to begin. I recommend keeping 1 bag slot empty of a bag to put your flute in to make switching between drum and flute more fluid. Or you can do like I do and keep the flute actually on your mouse pointer. That makes switching it out even faster.
<br />

<br />
1. Run through your camp running by as many of your mobs as possible. (That's why it's called &quot;swarm&quot; kiting, all the mobs chasing you look like a swarm of bugs.)
<br />

<br />
2. Once you have all the mobs you want turn around an while running backwards, hit your &quot;F8&quot; key to target the mob closest to you. Charm that mob, hit &quot;F8&quot; to target the next nearest mob. The reason: You want to keep your pet between you and the swarm--makes it easier to get the mobs to stick to the pet and not keep chasing you.
<br />

<br />
3. Tell your pet to attack the mob closest to you. If done properly, all the mobs will stop and attack your pet. And while this seems like cruel and unusual punishment for your poor pet, just remember it's the pet or you LOL! If you get a few stragglers still chasing you don't panic. Keep playing selos and run the spare mobs directly into the fray and they &quot;should&quot; get the idea of who they're supposed to be attacking. 
<br />

<br />
4. Once all the mobs are on your pet you want to be sure to have your pet targeted in case charm breaks early. That way you can re-charm the right mob. Once your pet gets very very low in HP switch to your flute and play invis song, breaking charm (remember to have pet targeted before you do this). 
<br />

<br />
5. After charm breaks put your drum back on, and chant kite the old pet until it dies, making sure to keep moving. Then you just start all over using F8 to target the nearest mob, charm it, F8 to target the next nearest mob, sic the pet on it. Keep doing this until all mobs are dead. Once you get the feel for the motions, you'll actually be able to loot the body while your next pet is fighting the swarm. 
<br />

<br />
Examples of easy mobs to swarm kite:
<br />
Giants
<br />
Kobolds
<br />
Werewolves in Plane of Nightmare
<br />
Flies in Plane of Disease
<br />
The humanoid mobs in Dulak
<br />
The Luggalds in Gunthak
<br />

<br />
Examples of mobs you shouldn't try swarming:
<br />
Anything that roots/snares/summons. If you get rooted you will die. Period.
<br />
Mobs that aren't social, meaning they don't help their buddies.
<br />
Mobs that need to be hit or cast on to aggro you.
<br />
Green con mobs, besides the fact that you won't get experience from them, most times they won't aggro you by running by them.
<br />

<br />
Hints and Tips:
<br />
*Always try to keep your pet targeted for easy re-charming.
<br />
*Use the highest lvl drum you have in your inventory for max chant damage.
<br />
*Never rely on the &quot;hide&quot; ability to break charm. Many times hide does not work and you'll just lose your pet and the experience from it.
<br />
*Consider, instead of your invis song, to do one of the many quests that yeild a clicky invis item. There is a ring from The Overthere, also a cloak. That will save you from having to switch instruments around.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
